00"></a></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" id="e-1627477816423" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1627477816423" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-exc=""><a href="https://methyl-life.com/pages/best-form-of-b12" target=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/26fe1ef6-94ed-401a-b6be-0924b4ece8cb/-/format/auto/-/preview/120x120/-/quality/lighter/" alt="Best Form Of B12 Vitamins" class="gf_image rte__no-indent gf_lazyload" data-gemlang="en" width="422" height="382" data-width="300px" data-height="auto" title="Best Form Of B12 Vitamins" natural-width="422" natural-height="382" data-lg-size="3000x3000"></a></div></div></div><div class="gf_column gf_col-xs-12 gf_col-sm-12 gf_col-lg-8 gf_col-md-8" id="c-1625746964108" data-id="1625746964108" style="display: block; flex-direction: unset; justify-content: unset; min-height: auto;"><div data-label="Row" data-key="row" id="r-1627477816303" class="gf_row gf_row-gap-0" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1627477816303" data-extraclass="" data-row-gap="0px"><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-12 gf_col-md-12 gf_col-sm-12 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1625751610245" data-id="1625751610245"><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" id="e-1627477816449" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1627477816449"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p><b>The Relationship Between an MTHFR Gene Mutation and Lupus</b></p></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1646013773858" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1646013773858"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left" data-gemlang="en"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Lupus is an autoimmune disease without a known cure. An estimated five million people worldwide have some form of lupus, but most are affected by systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), which will be the main focus of this article.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">SLE is diagnosed in around </span><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18163481/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">161,000 people in the US</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">, while around </span><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18163481/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">322,000 have definite or probable SLE</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">. It is most often seen in women of child-bearing age and is even more common in African-Americans, Asians, Hispanics, and Native Americans.</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">The pathophysiological understanding of lupus is constantly evolving. Recent research has identified several internal and external factors that may contribute to its onset, including hormones, genetics, and the environment. Among these is a possible link to functional polymorphisms of the gene encoding for the enzyme 5, 10- methylenetetrahydrofolate reductase (MTHFR), which may explain the high prevalence of elevated homocysteine levels among people living with lupus.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">This article will explain lupus and discuss how it may be linked to an MTHFR genetic mutation and what treatment options may be available.</span></p><p><!--StartFragment--><span id="docs-internal-guid-88aeb48e-7fff-ad3a-3aa7-9db8fa4054ea"></span><br class="Apple-interchange-newline"><!--EndFragment--></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" id="e-1632414828158" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1632414828158"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2><b>What Exactly is Lupus?</b></h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1646013845866" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1646013845866"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left" data-gemlang="en"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Lupus is a chronic </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3351863/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">inflammatory autoimmune disease</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> that affects multiple organ systems of the body. There are four main types of lupus: neonatal, discoid, drug-induced, and systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), which is the most common.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Lupus results in abnormal immunological function and the production of autoantibodies, leading to immune complexes that may destroy healthy tissue. Symptoms may range from none at all to periodic flares of varying severity.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">SLE causes the </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1769989/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">formation and deposition of autoantibodies</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> and immune complexes, leading to eventual organ damage. The skin, musculoskeletal system, and pulmonary system are primarily affected.</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3391953/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Typical signs and symptoms</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> of SLE include fever, fatigue, arthralgia&nbsp; and weight loss. However, every patient may experience symptoms differently.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">The most common sign is a red “butterfly” malar rash on the nose and cheeks following exposure to the sun. Other symptoms include skin conditions such as alopecia, Reynaud’s phenomenon, and sores in the mouth or nose.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">The musculoskeletal system is also affected, leading to joint pain and stiffness, muscle pain, and/or arthritis. Arthritis can affect minor or major joints, causing occasional or persistent inflammation.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Patients with pulmonary symptoms may experience painful breathing, coughing, and shortness of breath. SLE also affects the cardiovascular, gastrointestinal, renal, and hematological systems and the central nervous system (CNS).&nbsp;</span></p><p><!--StartFragment--><span id="docs-internal-guid-53c36629-7fff-2f50-d209-1008c14ff861"></span><br class="Apple-interchange-newline"><!--EndFragment--></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" id="e-1646013925162" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1646013925162"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2><b>Can an MTHFR Gene Mutation Cause Lupus?</b></h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1646013898153" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1646013898153"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left" data-gemlang="en"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Research is ongoing as to whether MTHFR mutations could cause lupus, and scientists have stated that more studies are needed to reach a consensus. That said, MTHFR mutations may worsen the effects of lupus.</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Numerous studies have identified MTHFR genetic mutations as </span><a href="https://methyl-life.com/blogs/mthfr/how-to-lower-homocysteine-mthfr" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">major contributors to elevated homocysteine</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> levels, along with </span><a href="https://methyl-life.com/blogs/mthfr/methylfolate-deficiency-symptoms" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">deficiencies in folate</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">, vitamin B6, or vitamin B12.</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Increased homocysteine levels are seen in approximately </span><a href="https://www.cureus.com/articles/21199-hyperhomocysteinemia-and-lupus-nephritis" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">15% of patients with lupus</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> and are associated with an increased risk of atherothrombotic events in these patients.</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Patients with lupus are found to have a significantly higher prevalence of the </span><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29501539/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">MTHFR homozygous 677TT</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> mutation compared to both Rheumatoid Arthritis (RA) patients and healthy controls.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">One study showed that </span><a href="https://acrabstracts.org/abstract/mthfr-polymorphisms-in-systemic-lupus-erythematosus-and-rheumatoid-arthritis-associations-with-intima-media-thickness-scores/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">25% of patients with SLE</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> had a TT double mutation on the 677 allele of the MTHFR gene while 10.5% had CC double mutations on the 1298 allele.</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p><!--StartFragment--><span id="docs-internal-guid-f9b9c418-7fff-b5f3-92c0-692bfaf650ec"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">A </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7535654/" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; color: rgb(17, 85, 204); background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; text-decoration-line: underline; text-decoration-skip-ink: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">meta-analysis</span></a><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"> of seven eligible studies involving 882 cases found that the MTHFR C677T (rs1801133) contributed to the susceptibility of SLE. However, the researchers pointed out that more case-control studies and larger sample sizes should be conducted to validate these findings.</span></span><!--EndFragment--><br></p><p><span><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"><br></span></span></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" id="e-1640961303549" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1640961303549"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2><b>Is Lupus Worse for Someone with MTHFR?</b></h2></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1646013957176" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1646013957176" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/1f509b06-fc59-4e0c-8f54-dd7268bc9729/-/format/auto/-/preview/120x120/-/quality/lighter/Is%20Lupus%20Worse%20for%20Someone%20with%20MTHFR.jpg" alt="Is Lupus Worse for Someone with MTHFR" class="gf_image gf_lazyload rte__no-indent" data-gemlang="en" width="1000" height="667" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="Is Lupus Worse for Someone with MTHFR" natural-width="1000" natural-height="667" data-lg-size="3000x3000"></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1646014010690" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1646014010690"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left" data-gemlang="en"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Every patient with lupus is affected differently. However, having both the symptoms of lupus and MTHFR may reduce the overall quality of life, particularly in the case of B12 deficiency and elevated homocysteine levels.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Hyperhomocysteinemia and </span><a href="https://www.cureus.com/articles/21199-hyperhomocysteinemia-and-lupus-nephritis" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">cardiovascular disease</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> are prevalent in both lupus patients and those with MTHFR&nbsp; mutations. Accelerated atherosclerosis (hardening of the arteries) is </span><a href="https://www.cureus.com/articles/21199-hyperhomocysteinemia-and-lupus-nephritis" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">more common in women with SLE </span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">compared to the general population.</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Those with lupus may develop </span><a href="https://musculoskeletalkey.com/constitutional-features-of-systemic-lupus-erythematosus/#bib1" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">antibodies to intrinsic factor</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">, reducing B12 absorption.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">One study found that </span><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12720045/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">46% of patients with SLE also have anemia</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">, and 24% had low levels of B12.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">A 2021 study found similar results, with SLE patients showing </span><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32702250/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">higher homocysteine levels</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> and lower vitamin B12 levels than those without SLE.</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p><!--StartFragment--><span id="docs-internal-guid-2fede4bc-7fff-6a8c-c0f7-92dbc1a3c908"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">B12 deficiency can increase the risk of </span><a href="https://methyl-life.com/blogs/mthfr/methylfolate-deficiency-symptoms" class="text-link" target=""><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; color: rgb(17, 85, 204); background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; text-decoration-line: underline; text-decoration-skip-ink: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">symptoms associated with MTHFR</span></a><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"> mutations, such as elevated homocysteine, </span><a href="https://methyl-life.com/blogs/b-12/what-happens-when-your-vitamin-b12-is-low" class="text-link"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; color: rgb(17, 85, 204); background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; text-decoration-line: underline; text-decoration-skip-ink: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">depression and anxiety</span></a><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">, </span><a href="https://methyl-life.com/blogs/mthfr/mthfr-and-fibromyalgia" class="text-link" target=""><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; color: rgb(17, 85, 204); background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; text-decoration-line: underline; text-decoration-skip-ink: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">chronic pain and fatigue</span></a><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">, nerve pain, and </span><a href="https://methyl-life.com/blogs/mthfr/mthfr-and-migraines" class="text-link" target=""><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; color: rgb(17, 85, 204); background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; text-decoration-line: underline; text-decoration-skip-ink: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">migraines</span></a><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">.</span></span><!--EndFragment--><br></p><p><span><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"><br></span></span></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" id="e-1640681952673" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1640681952673"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2><b>Are There Treatment Options?</b></h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1646014076490" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1646014076490"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left" data-gemlang="en"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">SLE is a chronic disease requiring long-term management. Lowering homocysteine concentrations is key to slowing the development and progression of further health issues.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><a href="https://methyl-life.com/blogs/mthfr/mthfr-b12" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target=""><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Sufficient vitamin B12</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> is key to managing healthy homocysteine levels. </span><a href="https://academic.oup.com/jn/article/126/suppl_4/1273S/4724802?login=false" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Supplementation of folic acid, vitamin B-12</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">, pyridoxine, betaine, dimethylglycine (DMG), and choline is also known to </span><a href="https://methyl-life.com/blogs/mthfr/how-to-lower-homocysteine-mthfr" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target=""><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">lower elevated homocysteine levels</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> in most patients with the MTHFR genetic defect.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Treatment with a combination of </span><a href="https://www.cureus.com/articles/21199-hyperhomocysteinemia-and-lupus-nephritis" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">vitamin B and folic acid</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> has been recommended for patients with lupus nephritis. That said, folic acid may not be the best option for those with MTHFR as it has been shown to have numerous drawbacks when </span><a href="https://methyl-life.com/blogs/mthfr/methylfolate-vs-folic-acid" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target=""><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">compared to methylfolate supplementation</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">.&nbsp;</span></p><p><!--StartFragment--><span id="docs-internal-guid-e2e81d21-7fff-c21b-9bd2-0d428195e67a"></span><br class="Apple-interchange-newline"><!--EndFragment--></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" id="e-1646014111448" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1646014111448"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2><b>How Could Supplements Help?</b></h2></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1646014139310" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1646014139310" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><a href="https://methyl-life.com/collections/active-b12/products/b12-complete-tablets" target=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/8a9dfcb5-7fdc-4d11-81f3-d1d8414c0c05/-/format/auto/-/preview/120x120/-/quality/lighter/Low%20levels%20of%20vitamin%20B12%20can%20be%20corrected%20with%20supplementation.jpg" alt="Low levels of vitamin B12 can be corrected with supplementation" class="gf_image gf_lazyload rte__no-indent" data-gemlang="en" width="1000" height="1000" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="Low levels of vitamin B12 can be corrected with supplementation" natural-width="1000" natural-height="1000" data-lg-size="3000x3000"></a></div></div></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1646014216886" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1646014216886"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left" data-gemlang="en"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Low levels of vitamin B12 can be </span><a href="https://methyl-life.com/blogs/mthfr/mthfr-b12" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target=""><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">corrected with supplementation</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">. </span><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">B12 works alongside folate and vitamin B6 to reduce homocysteine. When taken alongside folate, B12 helps to lower homocysteine levels more effectively than taking folate alone.</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Many commercial supplements contain the cyanocobalamin form of B12 that the body cannot use effectively, particularly when absorption is compromised.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">The most bioavailable forms of B12 </span><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28223907/" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">include</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> Hydroxocobalamin </span><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:Roboto,sans-serif;color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">(OHCbl)</span><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">, Adenosylcobalamin </span><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:Roboto,sans-serif;color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">(AdCbl)</span><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">, and Methylcobalamin (MeCbl). These forms are bioidentical to those naturally occurring in your body and can be used immediately.</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><a href="https://methyl-life.com/products/b12-complete-tablets" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target=""><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Methyl-Life’s® B12 Complete</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"> is a proprietary formula that contains all three active forms of B12. It’s </span><a href="https://methyl-life.com/blogs/mthfr/mthfr-vegan" style="text-decoration:none;" class="text-link" target=""><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#1155cc;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:underline;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">suitable for vegans</span></a><span style="font-size:12pt;font-family:'Helvetica Neue',sans-serif;color:#333333;background-color:#ffffff;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">, vegetarians, and those who have B12 deficiencies, Parkinson’s, Crohn’s, mental health issues, or people with MTR, MTRR, COMT, or other gene defects affecting B12 metabolism.</span></p><p><!--StartFragment--><span id="docs-internal-guid-e63fada4-7fff-8e5a-2e6c-488fcd12335f"></span><br class="Apple-interchange-newline"><!--EndFragment--></p></div></div></div></div><!--gfsplit--><div data-label="Row" class="gf_row gf_row-gap-0" id="r-1627477816293" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1627477816293" data-row-gap="0px" data-extraclass="" style="display: block; flex-wrap: unset; visibility: visible;" data-layout-lg="4+8" data-layout-md="4+8" data-layout-sm="12+12" data-layout-xs="12+12"><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-4 gf_col-md-4 gf_col-xs-12 gf_col-sm-12" id="c-1625746964083" data-id="1625746964083" style="display: block; flex-direction: